{{Infobox presenter | name = Glenn Hauser | image = | imagesize = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1945|04|12}} | birth_place = [[Berkeley, California]] | death_date = | death_place = | show = ''World of Radio'' | station = | network = | timeslot = | show2 = ''Mundo Radial'' | station2 = | network2 = | timeslot2 = | style = | country = [[United States]] | prevshow = | parents = | spouse(s) = | partner = | children = | web = [http://www.worldofradio.com Glenn Hauser's World of Radio] }}
'''Glenn Hauser''' (born April 12, 1945 in [[Berkeley, California]]) is an internationally known American [[DXing|DX]]er<ref name="Berg2008">{{cite book|last=Berg|first=Jerome S.|title=Listening on the short waves, 1945 to today|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZjP978PYo0MC&pg=PA222|accessdate=17 April 2011|date=October 2008|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-3996-6|pages=222–}}</ref><ref name="BennettHardy1993">{{cite book|last1=Bennett|first1=Hank|last2=Hardy|first2=David T.|last3=Yoder|first3=Andrew R.|title=The complete shortwave listener's handbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F_tmz9JIRHsC|accessdate=17 April 2011|date=September 1993|publisher=TAB Books|isbn=978-0-8306-4347-9|page=203}}</ref> and [[radio]] host from [[Enid, Oklahoma]]. He produces and presents a weekly 30-minute program, ''World Of Radio'',<ref name="League1997">{{cite book|last=American Radio Relay League|title=ARRL Operating Manual|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ICivfre46-QC|accessdate=17 April 2011|date=August 1997|publisher=American Radio Relay League|isbn=978-0-87259-614-6|pages=1–13}}</ref> heard on a number of [[Public broadcasting|non-commercial]] [[AM broadcasting|AM]] and [[FM broadcasting|FM]] stations throughout the [[United States|U.S.]] and worldwide on [[Shortwave radio|shortwave]].
Hauser began his broadcasting career on [[Radio Canada International]] during the late 1970s, providing DX tips on Sunday nights, and his tips also appeared on [[Radio Netherlands Worldwide|Radio Nederland's]] ''DX Juke Box'' program. He wrote for ''[[Popular Electronics]]'' and ''[[Modern Electronics]]'', and published ''Review of International Broadcasting''.<ref name=Harvey>Harvey, Sheldon, "[http://www.cidx.ca/sf/SF5Hauser.php Glenn Hauser interview] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706172348/http://www.cidx.ca/sf/SF5Hauser.php |date=2011-07-06 }}", ''CIDX Special Feature #5'', Summer 1999</ref>
==''World of Radio''== ''World Of Radio'' debuted in 1980 on [[WUOT]]-FM in [[Knoxville, Tennessee]], moving to shortwave two years later. The half-hour program consists of Hauser reading news about radio around the world in a characteristic monotone. Although ''World of Radio'' focuses on shortwave news, it covers all aspects of broadcasting. Most items are contributed by listeners to the program or DX publications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldofradio.com/dxlatest.txt|title=DX Listening Digest|accessdate=May 18, 2015}}</ref>
===''Mundo Radial''=== Hauser also produced ''Mundo Radial'', a [[Spanish language|Spanish]] edition of ''World of Radio'', from January 2002 to November 2007.<ref name=Mundo>[http://www.worldofradio.com/espanol.html Mundo Radial]</ref>
==''Review of International Broadcasting''== Hauser introduced ''Review of International Broadcasting'' in February 1977.<ref name=Berg /> The magazine published 154 issues, with columns such as "Listener Insights on Programming," "Radio Equipment Forum," "DX Listening Digest," "The Media Mind" and "Satellite Watch."<ref name=Berg /> Contributors included David Newkirk, Loren Cox and Juan Carlos Codina,<ref name=Berg>Berg, Jerome S., "Review of International Broadcasting (1977–1997)", 'Listening on the short waves, 1945 to today'', pg 221–223</ref> and ''RIB'' also featured columns from the BBC, John Norfolk and Alan Roe.<ref name=Berg /> It was published monthly during the 1970s and 1980s, later decreasing to quarterly and semiannually before ceasing publication in October 1997.<ref name=Berg /> ''RIB''{{'}}s successor, ''DX Listening Digest'', went online in 1999.<ref name=Berg />
=={{anchor|Religious views}}Political and religious views== Hauser is a political [[Liberalism|liberal]] and an [[Agnosticism|agnostic]],<!-- Think he identifies as atheist. --> which occasionally puts him at odds with the [[Christian fundamentalism|fundamentalist-dominated]] [[Shortwave broadcasting in the United States|American shortwave scene]] which carries ''World of Radio''.{{cn|date=October 2015}}
