{{Multiple image|direction=vertical|align=right |image1=Neotyphodium coenophialum.jpg |caption1=''[[Neotyphodium coenophialum]]'' in leaves of [[tall fescue]] |alt1=Fungal hyphae, blue-stained, among transparent plant cells. |image2=Root-nodule01.jpg |caption2=''[[Bradyrhizobium japonicum]]'' in root nodules of [[soybean]] |alt2=Transmission electron photograph, black and white, showing round bacterial cells. |width1=150 |width2=150 }}
'''Endophytes''' are micro-organisms living within the tissue of a [[plant]] as [[endosymbionts]], without causing symptoms of [[plant disease|disease]]. Some of them are [[mutualism (biology)|mutualistic]] symbionts with beneficial effects on their host, such as improved growth or resistance against disease or [[Abiotic stress|environmental stress]], and are being used as [[microbial inoculant]]s. However, [[pathogens]] and [[Saprotrophic nutrition|saprophytes]] may also be endophytic at some point of their life cycle. Endophytes are distinct from [[mycorrhizal]] fungi or [[rhizosphere]] microbes in that they live entirely within the plant. Most endophytes known are [[bacteria]] or [[fungi]], although there are also some endophytic [[algae]] and [[oomycetes]].
This list contains genera with endophytic species (but which may also have non-endophytic species). Species are only listed in notable cases. Where specific variants or [[cultivars]] of a species are endophytic, this is detailed on the taxon's page. The host range is "wide" when it does not include only a specific [[Lineage (evolution)|lineage]] of plants; in that case, the lineage is given.
