'''Tare weight''' {{IPAc-en|ˈ|t|ɛər}}, sometimes called '''[[unladen weight]]''', is the weight of an empty vehicle or container.<ref> {{Cite book | last = Soroka | first = W | title = Illustrated Glossary of Packaging Terminology | place = | publisher = Institute of Packaging Professionals | year = | volume = | edition = Second | url = http://www.iopp.org/i4a/pages/Index.cfm?pageID=1 }}</ref> By subtracting it from the [[gross weight]] ([[laden weight]]), the weight of the goods carried (the [[net weight]]) may be determined. This can be useful in computing the cost of the goods carried for purposes of [[tax]]ation or for [[Fee|tolls]] related to barge, rail, road, or other traffic, especially where the toll will vary with the value of the goods carried (''e.g.'', tolls on the [[Erie Canal]]). Tare weight is often published upon the sides of [[railway car]]s and transport vehicles to facilitate the computation of the load carried. Tare weight is also used in body composition assessment when doing underwater weighing.{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}}
The word ''[[wikt:tare#Etymology 2|tare]]'' originates from the [[Middle French]] word {{lang|frm|tare}} “wastage in goods, deficiency, imperfection” (15th {{abbr|c.|century}}), from [[Italy|Italian]] {{lang|it|tara}}, from [[Arabic]] {{lang|ar|طرح}} {{transl|ar|ṭarḥ}}, lit. “thing deducted or rejected”, from {{transl|ar|taraha}} “to reject”.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=tare |title=tare (2) |work=Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref>
Tare weight is accounted for in kitchen scales, [[analytical scale|analytical]] (scientific) and other [[weighing scale]]s which include a button that resets the zero of the scale display when an empty container is placed on the weighing platform, in order to subsequently display only the weight of the contents of the container.
Gross weight (the total weight) = net weight (the weight of the goods) + tare weight (the weight of the empty container).
